*Problem*

When a REST request is made that pages beyond the available results, it may return partial results that are part of the set.

*Expected results*

No results are returned for a query that has gone beyond its "last page"

*Actual results*

Results are returned based on their ordinal position in a given set of data *pre* filtering (i.e. we fetch results from the DB, then filter them and fill up a Page of results to return to the client). 

*Reproduce case*

 # I've created 6 projects, enable public access to the first and last project in the list (as listed on the project list)
 # As an anonymous user, make a request to {{/bitbucket/rest/api/1.0/projects?limit=5}} 
Note that 2 results will be returned, and that this is the last page of results.
{code:javascript}
{
  "size": 2,
  "limit": 5,
  "isLastPage": true,
  "values": [
    {
      "key": "PROJ1",
      "id": 1,
      "name": "Proj 1",
      "description": "Default configuration project #1",
      "public": true,
      "type": "NORMAL",
      "links": {
        "self": [
          {
            "href": "http://localhost:7991/bitbucket/projects/PROJ1"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "PROJ6",
      "id": 26,
      "name": "proj 6",
      "public": true,
      "type": "NORMAL",
      "links": {
        "self": [
          {
            "href": "http://localhost:7991/bitbucket/projects/PROJ6"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
  "start": 0
}
{code}
# Make another request, this time with a start param beyond the first page of results, e.g. {{/bitbucket/rest/api/1.0/projects?limit=5&start=5}}
  Note that 1 result is returned:
  {code:javascript}
{
  "size": 1,
  "limit": 5,
  "isLastPage": true,
  "values": [
    {
      "key": "PROJ6",
      "id": 26,
      "name": "proj 6",
      "public": true,
      "type": "NORMAL",
      "links": {
        "self": [
          {
            "href": "http://localhost:7991/bitbucket/projects/PROJ6"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
  "start": 5
}{code}

In Bitbucket Server 4.11 adaptive throttling increased the maximum number of concurrent hosting operations concurrently runnable from:
{noformat}
1.5*${scaling.concurrency}
{noformat}
to 
{noformat}
12*${scaling.concurrency}
{noformat}

This maximum appears to be too high and has caused problems such as:
- Out of memory errors
- Massive NFS performance degradation
- Insufficient protection from adaptive throttling problems such as BSERVDEV-15333

*Workaround:*
In Bitbucket Server 5.6.0 and later the value will be set like so:
{noformat}
throttle.resource.scm-hosting.adaptive.limit.max=4*${scaling.concurrency}
{noformat}

For Bitbucket Server 4.11 to 5.5 the same effect can be achieved by adding the above line to the bitbucket.properties file and then rebooting the instance. It is recommend that any cluster installation consider setting this limit to avoid saturating the NFS server with a large number of concurrent requests.

h3. Summary

Retrieve Tag Rest Endpoint returns 404 html response when it should return a JSON response. As per documentation:
 [Retrieve a tag in the specified repository.|https://developer.atlassian.com/static/rest/bitbucket-server/4.10.1/bitbucket-rest.html#idp709600]
h3. Environment

Bitbucket 4.14 +
h3. Steps to Reproduce

Enter the following URL for tag that doesn't exist.
/rest/api/1.0/projects/

\{projectKey}

/repos/

\{repositorySlug}

/tags/

\{name:.*}

This will return 404 HTML response instead of a JSON
h3. Expected Results

Expected JSON response. Example:
{code:java}
{
    "errors": [
        {
            "context": null,
            "message": "A detailed error message.",
            "exceptionName": null
        }
    ]
} 
{code}
h3. Actual Results

Received HTML 404 response
 * 404 Not Found

h3. Workaround

N/A
